# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: certificate-transparency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In cryptography, a **certificate authority** or **certification authority** (**CA**) is an entity that stores, signs, and issues digital certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made about the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A CA acts as a trusted third party—trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The format of these certificates is specified by the X.509 or EMV standard.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] One particularly common use for certificate authorities is to sign certificates used in HTTPS, the secure browsing protocol for the World Wide Web.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Another common use is in issuing identity cards by national governments for use in electronically signing documents.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Trusted certificates can be used to create secure connections to a server via the Internet.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A certificate is essential in order to circumvent a malicious party which happens to be on the route to a target server which acts as if it were the target.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Such a scenario is commonly referred to as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The client uses the CA certificate to authenticate the CA signature on the server certificate, as part of the authorizations before launching a secure connection.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Usually, client software—for example, browsers—include a set of trusted CA certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This makes sense, as many users need to trust their client software.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A malicious or compromised client can skip any security check and still fool its users into believing otherwise.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The clients of a CA are server supervisors who call for a certificate that their servers will bestow to users.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Commercial CAs charge money to issue certificates, and their customers anticipate the CA's certificate to be contained within the majority of web browsers, so that safe connections to the certified servers work efficiently out-of-the-box.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The quantity of web browsers, other devices, and applications which trust a particular certificate authority is referred to as ubiquity.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Mozilla, which is a non-profit business, issues several commercial CA certificates with its products.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] While Mozilla developed their own policy, the CA/Browser Forum developed similar guidelines for CA trust.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A single CA certificate may be shared among multiple CAs or their resellers.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A *root* CA certificate may be the base to issue multiple *intermediate* CA certificates with varying validation requirements.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In addition to commercial CAs, some non-profits issue publicly-trusted digital certificates without charge, for example Let's Encrypt.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Some large cloud computing and web hosting companies are also publicly-trusted CAs and issue certificates to services hosted on their infrastructure, for example IBM Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Large organizations or government bodies may have their own PKIs (public key infrastructure), each containing their own CAs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Any site using self-signed certificates acts as its own CA.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Each payment card presents along with its card data also the Card Issuer Certificate to the POS.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The Issuer Certificate is signed by EMV CA Certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The POS retrieves the public key of EMV CA from its storage, validates the Issuer Certificate and authenticity of the payment card before sending the payment request to the payment scheme.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Browsers and other clients of sorts characteristically allow users to add or do away with CA certificates at will.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] While server certificates regularly last for a relatively short period, CA certificates are further extended, so, for repeatedly visited servers, it is less error-prone importing and trusting the CA issued, rather than confirm a security exemption each time the server's certificate is renewed.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Less often, trustworthy certificates are used for encrypting or signing messages.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] CAs dispense end-user certificates too, which can be used with S/MIME.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] However, encryption entails the receiver's public key and, since authors and receivers of encrypted messages, apparently, know one another, the usefulness of a trusted third party remains confined to the signature verification of messages sent to public mailing lists.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Worldwide, the certificate authority business is fragmented, with national or regional providers dominating their home market.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This is because many uses of digital certificates, such as for legally binding digital signatures, are linked to local law, regulations, and accreditation schemes for certificate authorities.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] However, the market for globally trusted TLS/SSL server certificates is largely held by a small number of multinational companies.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This market has significant barriers to entry due to the technical requirements.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] While not legally required, new providers may choose to undergo annual security audits (such as WebTrust for certificate authorities in North America and ETSI in Europe) to be included as a trusted root by a web browser or operating system.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] As of 24 August 2020, 147 root certificates, representing 52 organizations, are trusted in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, 168 root certificates, representing 60 organizations, are trusted by macOS, and 255 root certificates, representing 101 organizations, are trusted by Microsoft Windows.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] As of Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean), Android currently contains over 100 CAs that are updated with each release.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Let's Encrypt is operated by the newly formed Internet Security Research Group, a California nonprofit recognized as federally tax-exempt.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] As of July 2024 the survey company W3Techs, which collects statistics on certificate authority usage among the Alexa top 10 million and the Tranco top 1 million websites, lists the five largest authorities by absolute usage share as below.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The commercial CAs that issue the bulk of certificates for HTTPS servers typically use a technique called "domain validation" to authenticate the recipient of the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The techniques used for domain validation vary between CAs, but in general domain validation techniques are meant to prove that the certificate applicant controls a given domain name, not any information about the applicant's identity.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Many Certificate Authorities also offer Extended Validation (EV) certificates as a more rigorous alternative to domain validated certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Extended validation is intended to verify not only control of a domain name, but additional identity information to be included in the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Some browsers display this additional identity information in a green box in the URL bar.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Domain validation suffers from certain structural security limitations.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In particular, it is always vulnerable to attacks that allow an adversary to observe the domain validation probes that CAs send.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] These can include attacks against the DNS, TCP, or BGP protocols (which lack the cryptographic protections of TLS/SSL), or the compromise of routers.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Such attacks are possible either on the network near a CA, or near the victim domain itself.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] One of the most common domain validation techniques involves sending an email containing an authentication token or link to an email address that is likely to be administratively responsible for the domain.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This could be the technical contact email address listed in the domain's WHOIS entry, or an administrative email like admin@, administrator@, webmaster@, hostmaster@ or postmaster@ the domain.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Some Certificate Authorities may accept confirmation using root@, info@, or support@ in the domain.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The theory behind domain validation is that only the legitimate owner of a domain would be able to read emails sent to these administrative addresses.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Domain validation implementations have sometimes been a source of security vulnerabilities.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In one instance, security researchers showed that attackers could obtain certificates for webmail sites because a CA was willing to use an email address like ssladmin@domain.com for domain.com, but not all webmail systems had reserved the "ssladmin" username to prevent attackers from registering it.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Prior to 2011, there was no standard list of email addresses that could be used for domain validation, so it was not clear to email administrators which addresses needed to be reserved.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The first version of the CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements, adopted November 2011, specified a list of such addresses.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This allowed mail hosts to reserve those addresses for administrative use, though such precautions are still not universal.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In January 2015, a Finnish man registered the username "hostmaster" at the Finnish version of Microsoft Live and was able to obtain a domain-validated certificate for live.fi, despite not being the owner of the domain name.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A CA issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The matching private key is not made available publicly, but kept secret by the end user who generated the key pair.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The certificate is also a confirmation or validation by the CA that the public key contained in the certificate belongs to the person, organization, server or other entity noted in the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A CA's obligation in such schemes is to verify an applicant's credentials, so that users and relying parties can trust the information in the issued certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] CAs use a variety of standards and tests to do so.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In essence, the certificate authority is responsible for saying "yes, this person is who they say they are, and we, the CA, certify that".
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] If the user trusts the CA and can verify the CA's signature, then they can also assume that a certain public key does indeed belong to whoever is identified in the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Public-key cryptography can be used to encrypt data communicated between two parties.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This can typically happen when a user logs on to any site that implements the HTTP Secure protocol.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In this example let us suppose that the user logs on to their bank's homepage www.bank.example to do online banking.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] When the user opens www.bank.example homepage, they receive a public key along with all the data that their web-browser displays.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The rest of the communication then proceeds using the new (disposable) symmetric key, so when the user enters some information to the bank's page and submits the page (sends the information back to the bank) then the data the user has entered to the page will be encrypted by their web browser.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Therefore, even if someone can access the (encrypted) data that was communicated from the user to www.bank.example, such eavesdropper cannot read or decipher it.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This mechanism is only safe if the user can be sure that it is the bank that they see in their web browser.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] If the user types in www.bank.example, but their communication is hijacked and a fake website (that pretends to be the bank website) sends the page information back to the user's browser, the fake web-page can send a fake public key to the user (for which the fake site owns a matching private key).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The user will fill the form with their personal data and will submit the page.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The fake web-page will then get access to the user's data.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This is what the certificate authority mechanism is intended to prevent.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A certificate authority (CA) is an organization that stores public keys and their owners, and every party in a communication trusts this organization (and knows its public key).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] When the user's web browser receives the public key from www.bank.example it also receives a digital signature of the key (with some more information, in a so-called X.509 certificate).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The browser already possesses the public key of the CA and consequently can verify the signature, trust the certificate and the public key in it: since www.bank.example uses a public key that the certification authority certifies, a fake www.bank.example can only use the same public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Since the fake www.bank.example does not know the corresponding private key, it cannot create the signature needed to verify its authenticity.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] It is difficult to assure correctness of match between data and entity when the data are presented to the CA (perhaps over an electronic network), and when the credentials of the person/company/program asking for a certificate are likewise presented.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This is why commercial CAs often use a combination of authentication techniques including leveraging government bureaus, the payment infrastructure, third parties' databases and services, and custom heuristics.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In some enterprise systems, local forms of authentication such as Kerberos can be used to obtain a certificate which can in turn be used by external relying parties.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Notaries are required in some cases to personally know the party whose signature is being notarized; this is a higher standard than is reached by many CAs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] 2. a contract relating to such transaction may not be denied legal effect, validity or enforceability solely because an electronic signature or electronic record was used in its formation.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Despite the security measures undertaken to correctly verify the identities of people and companies, there is a risk of a single CA issuing a bogus certificate to an imposter.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] It is also possible to register individuals and companies with the same or very similar names, which may lead to confusion.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] To minimize this hazard, the *certificate transparency* initiative proposes auditing all certificates in a public unforgeable log, which could help in the prevention of phishing.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In large-scale deployments, Alice may not be familiar with Bob's certificate authority (perhaps they each have a different CA server), so Bob's certificate may also include his CA's public key signed by a different CA2, which is presumably recognizable by Alice.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This process typically leads to a hierarchy or mesh of CAs and CA certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Revocation is performed by the issuing CA, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The CA/Browser Forum publishes the Baseline Requirements, a list of policies and technical requirements for CAs to follow.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] These are a requirement for inclusion in the certificate stores of Firefox and Safari.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] On April 14, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum passed a ballot to reduce SSL/TLS certificates to 47 day maximum term by March 15, 2029.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] If the CA can be subverted, then the security of the entire system is lost, potentially subverting all the entities that trust the compromised CA.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] For example, suppose an attacker, Eve, manages to get a CA to issue to her a certificate that claims to represent Alice.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] That is, the certificate would publicly state that it represents Alice, and might include other information about Alice.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Some of the information about Alice, such as her employer name, might be true, increasing the certificate's credibility.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Eve, however, would have the all-important private key associated with the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Eve could then use the certificate to send a digitally signed email to Bob, tricking Bob into believing that the email was from Alice.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Bob might even respond with encrypted email, believing that it could only be read by Alice, when Eve is actually able to decrypt it using the private key.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] A notable case of CA subversion like this occurred in 2001, when the certificate authority VeriSign issued two certificates to a person claiming to represent Microsoft.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The certificates have the name "Microsoft Corporation", so they could be used to spoof someone into believing that updates to Microsoft software came from Microsoft when they actually did not.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Microsoft and VeriSign took steps to limit the impact of the problem.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In 2008, Comodo reseller Certstar sold a certificate for mozilla.com to Eddy Nigg, who had no authority to represent Mozilla.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In 2011 fraudulent certificates were obtained from Comodo and DigiNotar, allegedly by Iranian hackers.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] There is evidence that the fraudulent DigiNotar certificates were used in a man-in-the-middle attack in Iran.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In 2012, it became known that Trustwave issued a subordinate root certificate that was used for transparent traffic management (man-in-the-middle) which effectively permitted an enterprise to sniff SSL internal network traffic using the subordinate certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In 2012, the Flame malware (also known as SkyWiper) contained modules that had an MD5 collision with a valid certificate issued by a Microsoft Terminal Server licensing certificate that used the broken MD5 hash algorithm.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The authors thus was able to conduct a collision attack with the hash listed in the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] In 2015, a Chinese certificate authority named MCS Holdings and affiliated with China's central domain registry issued unauthorized certificates for Google domains.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Google thus removed both MCS and the root certificate authority from Chrome and have revoked the certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] An attacker who steals a certificate authority's private keys is able to forge certificates as if they were CA, without needed ongoing access to the CA's systems.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Key theft is therefore one of the main risks certificate authorities defend against.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Publicly trusted CAs almost always store their keys on a hardware security module (HSM), which allows them to sign certificates with a key, but generally prevent extraction of that key with both physical and software controls.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] CAs typically take the further precaution of keeping the key for their long-term root certificates in an HSM that is kept offline, except when it is needed to sign shorter-lived intermediate certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The intermediate certificates, stored in an online HSM, can do the day-to-day work of signing end-entity certificates and keeping revocation information up to date.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] CAs sometimes use a key ceremony when generating signing keys, in order to ensure that the keys are not tampered with or copied.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The critical weakness in the way that the current X.509 scheme is implemented is that any CA trusted by a particular party can then issue certificates for any domain they choose.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Such certificates will be accepted as valid by the trusting party whether they are legitimate and authorized or not.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This is a serious shortcoming given that the most commonly encountered technology employing X.509 and trusted third parties is the HTTPS protocol.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] As all major web browsers are distributed to their end-users pre-configured with a list of trusted CAs that numbers in the dozens this means that any one of these pre-approved trusted CAs can issue a valid certificate for any domain whatsoever.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] The industry response to this has been muted.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] Given that the contents of a browser's pre-configured trusted CA list is determined independently by the party that is distributing or causing to be installed the browser application there is really nothing that the CAs themselves can do.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] This issue is the driving impetus behind the development of the DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) protocol.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-authority] If adopted in conjunction with Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) DANE will greatly reduce if not eliminate the role of trusted third parties in a domain's PKI.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency makes public all issued certificates in the form of a distributed ledger, giving website owners and auditors the ability to detect and expose inappropriately issued certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Work on Certificate Transparency first began in 2011 after the certificate authority DigiNotar became compromised and started issuing malicious certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Google engineers submitted a draft to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in 2012.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] This effort resulted in IETF RFC 6962, a standard defining a system of public logs to record all certificates issued by publicly trusted certificate authorities, allowing efficient identification of mistakenly or maliciously issued certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The certificate transparency system consists of a system of append-only certificate logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Logs are operated by many parties, including browser vendors and certificate authorities.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Certificates that support certificate transparency must include one or more *signed certificate timestamps* (SCTs), which is a promise from a log operator to include the certificate in their log within a *maximum merge delay* (MMD).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] At some point within the maximum merge delay, the log operator adds the certificate to their log.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Each entry in a log references the hash of a previous one, forming a Merkle tree.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The *signed tree head* (STH) references the current root of the Merkle tree.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The CA issues a special *precertificate*, a certificate which carries a poison extension signaling that it should not be accepted by user agents.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The CA sends the precertificate to logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Logs return corresponding SCTs to the CA.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The CA attaches SCTs collected from logs as an X.509 extension to the final certificate and provides it to the applicant.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Finally, the CA may decide to log the final certificate as well.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Let's Encrypt E1 CA, for example, logs both precertificates and final certificates (see CA crt.sh profile page under 'issued certificates' section), whereas Google GTS CA 2A1 does not (see crt.sh profile page).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Due to the large quantities of certificates issued with the Web PKI, certificate transparency logs can grow to contain many certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] This large quantity of certificates can cause strain on logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Temporal sharding is a method to reduce the strain on logs by sharding a log into multiple logs, and having each shard only accept precertificates and certificates with an expiration date in a particular time period (usually a calendar year).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Cloudflare's Nimbus series of logs was the first to use temporal sharding.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] One of the problems with digital certificate management is that fraudulent certificates take a long time to be spotted, reported and revoked.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] An issued certificate not logged using Certificate Transparency may never be spotted at all.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The main advantage with Certificate Transparency is the ability for cyber security teams to defend companies and organisations by monitoring for suspicious domains registering certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] The new certificates for these suspicious domains may have similar names to other legitimate domains and are designed to be used to support malicious activities such as phishing attacks.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency puts cyber security teams in control and enables them to issue domain take down orders for suspicious domains and allows them to apply cyber security controls on web proxies and email gateways for immediate protection.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Domain names that are used on internal networks and have certificates issued by certificate authorities become publicly searchable as their certificates are added to CT logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency depends on verifiable Certificate Transparency logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] A log appends new certificates to an ever-growing Merkle hash tree.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] A log may accept certificates that are not yet fully valid and certificates that have expired.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] There are two primary categories of monitors: log integrity monitors (also referred to as log verifiers or log auditors) and tracking monitors.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Some companies offering monitoring services collect data from all logs and provide paid services for domain tracking.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] For example, a domain owner can register for Cloudflare's services, which globally monitor all logs and send email updates whenever a certificate is issued for their domain, allowing them control over all certificates issued.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Large organizations can maintain their own monitors, which continuously scan for new certificate issued for their domains.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] If a certificate authority (CA) attempts to issue a "bad" certificate for one of these domains (intentionally or unintentionally), the monitor will quickly detect it.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Two popular APIs for research and tracking are Sectigo's crt.sh and Cloudflare MerkleTown.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] These tools facilitate the monitoring of certificate issuance and help organizations stay on top of the security of their domains.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] While there is an additional consideration of monitoring the monitors themselves, the likelihood of a significant impact on system performance or security due to misbehavior of a single monitor is low.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] This is because there are numerous log monitors, providing a layered approach to security and minimizing the risk of a single point of failure.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Apple and Google have separate log programs with distinct policies and lists of trusted logs.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency logs maintain their own root stores and only accept certificates that chain back to the trusted roots.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] A number of misbehaving logs have been publishing inconsistent root stores in the past.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] A new structure for logs is based on dividing the Merkle Tree into tiles.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] This structure is expected to be faster, easier to operate, and to provide much smaller merge delays (the current Maximum Merge Delay is 24 hours).
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Chrome has updated its Certificate Transparency (CT) policy to accept SCTs from the new static-CT-API logs only if an SCT from an RFC 6962 log is also present, and it intends to complete the migration to static-CT-API CT logs by the end of 2025.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In 2011, a reseller of the certificate authority Comodo was attacked and the certificate authority DigiNotar was compromised, demonstrating existing flaws in the certificate authority ecosystem and prompting work on various mechanisms to prevent or monitor unauthorized certificate issuance.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Google employees Ben Laurie, Adam Langley and Emilia Kasper began work on an open source framework for detecting mis-issued certificates the same year.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In 2012, they submitted the first draft of the standard to IETF under the code-name "Sunlight".
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In March 2013, Google launched its first certificate transparency log.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In June 2013, RFC 6962 "Certificate Transparency" was published, based on the 2012 draft.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In September 2013, DigiCert became the first certificate authority to implement Certificate Transparency.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In 2015, Google Chrome began requiring Certificate Transparency for newly issued Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] It began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates newly issued by Symantec from June 1, 2016, after they were found to have issued 187 certificates without the domain owners' knowledge.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Since April 2018, this requirement has been extended to all certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] On March 23, 2018, Cloudflare announced its own CT log named *Nimbus*.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In May 2019, certificate authority Let's Encrypt launched its own CT log called Oak.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Since February 2020, it is included in approved log lists and is usable by all publicly trusted certificate authorities.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In December 2021, RFC 9162 "Certificate Transparency Version 2.0" was published.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] Version 2.0 includes major changes to the required structure of the log certificate, as well as support for Ed25519 as a signature algorithm of SCTs and support for including certificate inclusion proofs with the SCT.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] However, it has not seen industry adoption and is considered dead on arrival.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In February 2022, Google published an update to their CT policy, which removes the requirement for certificates to include a SCT from their own CT log service, matching all the requirements for certificates to those previously published by Apple.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In February 2025, Mozilla Firefox desktop version 135 began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates issued by a certificate authority in Mozilla's Root CA Program.
[src:certificate-transparency/certificate-transparency] In Certificate Transparency Version 2.0, a log must use one of the algorithms in the IANA registry "Signature Algorithms".
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:certificate-transparency/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In public-key cryptography, a **public key fingerprint** is a short sequence of bytes used to identify a longer public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Fingerprints are created by applying a cryptographic hash function to a public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Since fingerprints are shorter than the keys they refer to, they can be used to simplify certain key management tasks.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] The data produced in the previous step is hashed with a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-1 or SHA-2.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] If desired, the hash function output can be truncated to provide a shorter, more convenient fingerprint.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] This process produces a short fingerprint which can be used to authenticate a much larger public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] For example, whereas a typical RSA public key will be 2048 bits in length or longer, typical MD5 or SHA-1 fingerprints are only 128 or 160 bits in length.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] When displayed for human inspection, fingerprints are usually encoded into hexadecimal strings.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] These strings are then formatted into groups of characters for readability.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] When a public key is received over an untrusted channel, such as the Internet, the recipient often wishes to authenticate the public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Fingerprints can help accomplish this, since their small size allows them to be passed over trusted channels where public keys won't easily fit.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] For example, if Alice wishes to authenticate a public key as belonging to Bob, she can contact Bob over the phone or in person and ask him to read his fingerprint to her, or give her a scrap of paper with the fingerprint written down.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Alice can then check that this trusted fingerprint matches the fingerprint of the public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Exchanging and comparing values like this is much easier if the values are short fingerprints instead of long public keys.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Fingerprints can also be useful when automating the exchange or storage of key authentication data.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] For example, if key authentication data needs to be transmitted through a protocol or stored in a database where the size of a full public key is a problem, then exchanging or storing fingerprints may be a more viable solution.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In addition, fingerprints can be queried with search engines in order to ensure that the public key that a user just downloaded can be seen by third party search engines.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] If the search engine returns hits referencing the fingerprint linked to the proper site(s), one can feel more confident that the key is not being injected by an attacker, such as a Man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] PGP developed the PGP word list to facilitate the exchange of public key fingerprints over voice channels.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In systems such as SSH, users can exchange and check fingerprints manually to perform key authentication.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] Once a user has accepted another user's fingerprint, that fingerprint (or the key it refers to) will be stored locally along with a record of the other user's name or address, so that future communications with that user can be automatically authenticated.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In systems such as X.509-based PKI, fingerprints are primarily used to authenticate root keys.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] These root keys issue certificates which can be used to authenticate user keys.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] This use of certificates eliminates the need for manual fingerprint verification between users.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In systems such as PGP or Groove, fingerprints can be used for either of the above approaches: they can be used to authenticate keys belonging to other users, or keys belonging to certificate-issuing authorities.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In PGP, normal users can issue certificates to each other, forming a web of trust, and fingerprints are often used to assist in this process (e.g., at key-signing parties).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In systems such as CGA or SFS and most cryptographic peer-to-peer networks, fingerprints are embedded into pre-existing address and name formats (such as IPv6 addresses, file names or other identification strings).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] If addresses and names are already being exchanged through trusted channels, this approach allows fingerprints to piggyback on them.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In PGP, most keys are created in such a way that what is called the "key ID" is equal to the lower 32 or 64 bits respectively of a key fingerprint.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] PGP uses key IDs to refer to public keys for a variety of purposes.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] These are not, properly speaking, fingerprints, since their short length prevents them from being able to securely authenticate a public key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] 32bit key ids should not be used as current hardware can generate a colliding 32bit key id in just 4 seconds.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] The primary threat to the security of a fingerprint is a second-preimage attack, where an attacker constructs a key pair whose public key hashes to a fingerprint that matches the victim's fingerprint.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] The attacker could then present his public key in place of the victim's public key to masquerade as the victim.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] A secondary threat to some systems is a collision attack, where an attacker constructs multiple key pairs which hash to his own fingerprint.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] This may allow an attacker to repudiate signatures he has created, or cause other confusion.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] To prevent preimage attacks, the cryptographic hash function used for a fingerprint should possess the property of second preimage resistance.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] If collision attacks are a threat, the hash function should also possess the property of collision-resistance.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] While it is acceptable to truncate hash function output for the sake of shorter, more usable fingerprints, the truncated fingerprints must be long enough to preserve the relevant properties of the hash function against brute-force search attacks.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In practice, most fingerprints commonly used today are based on non-truncated MD5 or SHA-1 hashes.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] As of 2017, collisions but not preimages can be found in MD5 and SHA-1.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] The future is therefore likely to bring increasing use of newer hash functions such as SHA-256.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] However, fingerprints based on SHA-256 and other hash functions with long output lengths are more likely to be truncated than (relatively short) MD5 or SHA-1 fingerprints.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] In situations where fingerprint length must be minimized at all costs, fingerprint security can be boosted by increasing the cost of calculating the fingerprint.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-fingerprint] For example, in the context of Cryptographically Generated Addresses, this is called "Hash Extension" and requires anyone calculating a fingerprint to search for a hashsum starting with a fixed number of zeroes, which is assumed to be an expensive operation.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:certificate-transparency/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
